				\begin{document}$$\tau$$\end{document}τ in between both pulses. The resulting interferogram is in consequence tilted and shows modulations in the spectral and spatial domain. The 2D Fourier transform of this tilted spatial-spectral interferogram gives non-overlapped access to the DC and AC terms, separated in the Fourier domain, or k-t-space, due to the 2D characteristics. The standard SRSI algorithm32 can be used to recover the temporal amplitude and phase or directly obtain the temporal contrast, thanks to the AC cross-field correlation \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
